description.text: Getting some designs laser cut and wondering what to do with the unused space? Why not fill it with something fun like Lego-compatible blocks? Note: I have not confirmed these work. I just wanted to fill up some space on a heated build platform design I\'m hoping to send off to Ponoko shortly. Update 2009/12/11: I uploaded the QCAD DXF (LCBlockFiller.20091210.dxf) and source SVG (LCBlockFiller.20091210.inkscape.svg) I sent off to Ponoko to figure out the service and exercise my QCAD+Inkscape design flow. QCAD calculates the total length of the "CuttingLines_0p003mm" layer geometry as 10931.7mm (~430.4"). Note: I created this file by laying down 8mm-spaced grid lines and placing peg outlines at the center of each so I wouldn't get double-counting of internal lines. Update 2010/01/04: Test print from Ponoko arrived! I need to take some measurements and tweak designs to better accommodate the laser's kerf. Disclaimer: LEGO is a trademark of the LEGO Group and these explorations are in no way associated with LEGO Group. Heck! The files are CC-licensed; nothing to stop them embracing and extending it themselves if they so chose! ;-)

• Read the DXF into your favorite CAD program and sprinkle liberally in the empty spaces.

  • Send to laser cutter.
    • The interlocking blocks should be cut from a material 3mm to be Lego-compatible at right-angles. Other blocks should be Lego compatible if cut from 3mm (~1/8"), 6mm (~1/4"), or 10mm (~3/8") thick material. Important Note: You do want to keep the little inner ~5mm diameter cylinders.
  • Place the cut-out block on a piece of real Lego-type block so the inner 5mm diameter cylinders pop out.
    • I shaped the cylinders/holes so the major diameter is 4.9mm to match real Lego peg dimensions and added little 0.05mm knobs around the periphery at 0, 90, 180 and 270 degrees.
  • Pull the knobs out, rotate them 45 degrees and force them back into the hole.
    • Lego knobs are ~1.8mm high. Assuming the laser cutter kerf (the gap left by the vaporized material) isn\'t too wide the knobs should stay in place. If friction isn\'t enough and they don\'t stick, a little dab of cyanoacrylate glue should do the trick.

The Sous Vide rig described in Make: 25 http://makezine.com/25/sousvide mounts the immersion heaters permanently to the bottom of the control box, and then the whole works sits up on top of the water bath. Many have built modular versions, with an outlet on the control box to power immersion heaters, or some other heat source. This Thing is designed to mount three immersion heaters atop the ceramic insert (crock?) of my oval shaped Crock Pot. I split it into two pieces for printing on my Ultimaker. This first print was intended to be a prototype, but it works fine for now. The attached Solidworks 2011 file and STL files are updated with a couple of fixes that I would implement if I made it again. Most notably, when I split the part in half, I gave the split line a width of 1mm so there will (theoretically) be some clearance between the two halves when they come together. But I'll probably redesign it completely before printing again, with the heaters in more of a triangular arrangement. And/or perhaps for a larger bath, bucket, or something like that. This was designed for the "Crock-Pot SCVT650-PS 6-1/2-Quart Programmable Touch Screen Slow Cooker" that I already own.

• Order an Ultimaker.
  • Wait about 6 weeks.
  • Build it and make a few things
  • Why are you building a Sous Vide cooker when you can be making things with your Ultimaker?
  • Oh right, why not do both.
  • Design this Thing.
  • Start printing the first half. Go away for 3 hour 10 minutes.
  • Print the other half. Go away for 3 hours 10 minutes.
  • Simply snap the two halves together with the immersion heater placed in the holes, and you're done.
  • Oh, they don't even remotely fit together? But they fit perfectly on the screen!
  • Dremel the daylights out of the notches until the two halves fit together.
  • Think about doing a more careful job calibrating 3D printing profile settings.
  • OK, stop thinking about that now, and continue.
  • Wrap a long shoelace around the two halves, twist a pencil or something around in the lace to crank the two halves together tightly.
  • Cyanoacrylate (crazy-glue) the halves together. Go away for a while to avoid the fumes.
  • Better idea: use a hot-glue gun to pave in all the dremel gouges, seal up the gaps, and position the immersion heaters.
  • Win
    • More details of the build here: http://www.flickr.com/photos/cbonsig/sets/72157628184626549/

This is a simple clip for LEDs which come 4 very bright white on a small PC board for $1.99 from the following source, and quite possibly others: http://www.goldmine-elec-products.com/prodinfo.asp?number=G15554 4 of these bright LEDs clipped to the Z stage of a ThingOMatic on each side of the extruder provides a good view of prints, especially at the beginning when you really want to see how the plastic is sticking to the platform. These may also be useful for any other printers or devices that use 5mm plywood or material of a similar thickness.

• Purchase two of the above LED strips, or acquire in some other way, such as making your own ~10x40mm pc board.
  • Remove LED pc board from case, which I did by breaking it open with pliers.
  • Print two of the clips.
  • Wire the two pc boards in series (they work on 5-9 volts DC, so in series connected to 12V each board gets 6 V). In layman's terms, connect the red on one board to the black on the other. The other red and black become your leads to your power.
  • Add a cable (black/red if you have it) long enough to connect the other leads to the base of your printer. Don't forget to insulate all connections with heat shrink, Kapton tape, etc. You don't want to short out the 12V supply during a print!
  • Wire up the far end of the cable to 12V from the PC power supply. I used a 4 pin Molex adapter that pulled out the 12V to a 3 pin fan header that I had, but there are lots of 12V sources that could be used. You could also attach these in parallel with the Extruder fan, I suppose, but I didn't try that. You could also put in a switch if you want, I didn't bother as I can just unplug the little header if need be.
  • Put one clip on each side of the extruder nozzle with the LEDs pointing down. You may need to sand or file the notch to make it fit; I kept tolerances small so that the clips would be tight and unlikely to fall off into your print.
  • Enjoy the nice light on your plaform!

description.text:
This is a further remix of my own Tantillus upper Slide-ON corners - which is a remix of the original top corners.

This version

Now there are room for adding spacers or thrust bearings between the XY rod bearings and GT2 pulleys. This will help keep the rods and the entire XY structre in place. Just like the Ultimaker.
Easier to make room for wires for front mounted LEDs like the UM - I ended up putting wires up over the rod though, but you do require a bit less material and time when printing.

BOM

  • Print in ABS if you use heated chamber and print very hot materials like Polycarbonate
  • You CAN print the spacers, but I recommend using something slippery for it. I have used 5mm ABS spacers (bought) and also tested using 5mm thrust-bearings with good results.
  • In addition you need 0,8mm normal spacer/shim with 8mm center hole and 16 outer diameter.

Recommendations

  • I recommend you take a look at my Tantillus Compact Ultimaker Slider Adapters

description.text: This is very much a work in progress, and is not simple to print yet. Please forgive my yellow "White" cane :D I just couldn't resist (and I'm running out of white). This is intended to be a "White cane" (http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/White_cane) for the blind or visually impaired... Warning I have no experience designing disability assistance devices nor do I have any experience with the blind or visually impaired, but I am open to feedback and willing to learn. I think the diamiter is a bit too wide and I'm planning to thin down the next version (I keep thinking in diamiter, but OpenSCAD thinks in radius). Again, I'm not sure how wide a normal white cane is so feedback from people who might know better would be great. You will need to print at least one handle and one end piece (warning: the end piece ball will require at least a raft... mine still moved... improvements to this are already planned) The modular design is intended to accomidate a variety of users and cane styles. I was origionally thinking that two mid segments would be appropriate for a "Symbol Cane", but after printing I think maybe three would be better. For a "Guide Cane" at least four or five mid segments would be required, and for a "Long Cane" six or more might be appropriate. The current design should probably not be used as a long cane as the segments just use friction to hold together and the join might not be strong enough. I plan to "lock" the pieces together in a future version. Any advise on locking mechanisms that are "blind friendly" would be appreciated. I'm also planning to smooth out the mid section in the next iteration. This is also my entry for the "Print to improve life quality"(http://forums.reprap.org/read.php?282,220067) competition. Wish me luck.

comments.text:
Hello! I actually came here because I lost my cane the day before hurricane Irma here in Florida, US. I have an idea for the locking mechanism that should more then suffice without having to worry about finding out the spring properties of PLA, ABS, etc. What I was thinking, is rather a push, twist, pull, and twist locking mechanism. By this I sorta like the gift maze box found here: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:818193
Of course, nothing that intricate. The way it works is that it has a little half-sphere sticking out of the piece to be inserted, and there is a ridge that received is. Once it goes in all the way to the bottom in a straight line, you can twist it right, pull up slightly, and pull to the left to lock it in place!

title: Samsung Galaxy S II Cradle v1

description.text: This is my first design in Sketchup and the first real piece printed on the new printer, Both the Sketchup skills and printer need a bit of fine tuning.

Just print both parts and I have glued them together with Super Glue and used some kicker to set the glue quicker, seems to be ok still.
Next versions might include a slot in the base for the charge/USB cable so it can charge while in the cradle.
This was more a bit of a test for me to learn Sketchup and actually print something other then just test objects.
The holder part can be matched up with different bases for different mounting options, another I'll be working will be for the car, although might need a whole new holder for Landscape orientation.
Just updated some photos of the finished product with some better quality printouts, still not 100% but much better.
Also added a slight variation of the main holder piece that allows for a charge cable to fit through, Hopefully this one will go in the car with the new base I have also attached, still haven't printed these yet still working on the base design and still needs some tweeking.

This is a replacement stake for the Harbor Freight "Solar Brushed Nickel LED Path Light" (item #60755). I suspect that it will work for many other yard lights as well. Certainly you could modify the OpenSCAD file to make appropriate adjustments for your particular light. Note that this part will require printing with support. See the instructions for more details. Here is a link to the original yard light:
http://www.harborfreight.com/solar-brushed-nickel-led-path-lights-2-piece-60755.html

You can either take the part as is and print it from the STL or you can modify the OpenSCAD to resize / scale to your needs. I rotated the stake so it prints lying down and rotated so that two of the "fins" on the side of the stake are against the platform. Because of all the slops and angles, you will need to print this with support. On my Solidoodle2, using Slic3r, I turned the support down a bit (to about 35 degrees) so that it only printed along the edges of the stake rather than filling in the entire underside between the two 'fins'.

comments.text: My dog keeps wandering through the shrubs and breaking the lights.  I decided to draw one up and found this instead.  It was a perfect fit.  I printed it vertically with support on glass with purple glue stick.  Worked perfectly.  I needed 3 and printed 6 to have some spares.  Great job!
comments.author: redbaron12

comments.text: Glad you found it useful.  Sorry the dog keeps breaking your lights though!  :)
comments.author: redbaron12

title: Big Red Button Sphere of Unkown

description.text:
I found a Big Red Button in a junk box left over from a project and while unable to sleep I spent too long making up what was a simple sphere in Tinkercad into a reinforced one with a matching removable base.

I had no idea, what so ever, what I'm it was or was going to be. Just that a button needed a big sphere to match it.
It might blow up the world, beep loudly randomly when the button is pressed, simply turn off never to come back on, be the start of a robot project that escapes when you try and get close, be a pure 'art' object('maybe an android breast' was one suggestion), an emergency stop, a voice response magic-8-ball or anything else.
Right now it sits on a table and taunts me with it's possibilities.

The sphere is 135mm dia. at the base and 63mm high. It was going to include screw holes, thus the rounded bits inside. I will add them with a drill later if needed. The base seems to push on quite well on it's own.
The button is 46mm at the widest part, 40.5mm where it fits into the sphere and almost 70mm total length. It's a tight fit into the hole, if not a drop or two of hot glue would do a good job.
The top was printed pretty heavy, 3 perimeters and 40% infill to make for a solid feeling sphere. This may be a bit excessive, it was a 15 hour print. It needs no supports.

nanowii case bottom

Filament Wipe Insert

This is a thing that sits between your 3D printer filament and extruder. It wipes any crumbs, dust, grease, hand oil, crust, wax, and other gnarly stuff off of the filament before it goes into your expensive, finicky, testy, often depressed and touchy hot end.

There are many others like this, but this one is mine. I wanted a version that was easier for me to parametrize, so I made my own in Onshape here.

How to Use the Thing

You stuff some natural sponge or microfiber into the inside. Then thread the filament through the cap, through the spongey/microfibery inside, out the bottom, and screw the thing together. It is now wiping up a storm, which should help your hot end through those rough patches when it just doesn't want to go to the party, it just wants to stay home and read a book, you know?

How to Print the Thing

I used PLA for the one in the photos, at medium (0.2mm) resolution on my (friend's) Printrbot Simple Metal. It should print fine with no rafts or supports, but you should always throw a brim on there to keep it real.

An enclosure to house a solid state relay (SSR) to interface with the Heatermeter BBQ controller.

It's used to turn the Heatermeter into a Sous Vide controller to regulate water bath temperatures. I built it to control a slow cooker, and although the SSR has a bit of passive cooling with exposure at the bottom, I would not suggest running this with high amperage equipment.

The bottom mounts with printed female M6 threads, and the caps are pressed on to act as feet for M6 Hex Cap screws. (Allen Head).
More information can be found on the Heatermeter forum here ...

I know, there are already a lot of them, but I wanted to make one by myself, to welcome my brand new 3B model… ;)

Warning : this box is fit for traditionnal computer use and media center. There are no holes for PiCam connector and GPIO connectors.

You'll need 4 M3x16 screws and nuts to close it. Be careful not to tighten the screws too much, or you might break the printed parts (always be gentle when tightening screws in printed parts anyway, specially with PLA).
